<paragraph id="8BED0D5D0949B217ECC5F9CC23D04CF6" blockId="29.[151,1437,1552,1905]" pageId="29" pageNumber="480">
<emphasis id="B926D14F0949B217ECC5F9CC21AE4C03" bold="true" box="[199,421,1552,1578]" pageId="29" pageNumber="480">Short description:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C5276DE0949B217EDB2F9CD22644C03" baseAuthorityName="Boulenger" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[432,623,1552,1579]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Awaous" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="480" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="jayakari">
<emphasis id="B926D14F0949B217EDB2F9CD22644C03" box="[432,623,1552,1579]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="480">Awaous jayakari</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName id="4C5276DE0949B217EF2EF9CD23D24C03" baseAuthorityName="Schneider" baseAuthorityYear="1801" box="[812,985,1553,1579]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Awaous" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="480" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="commersoni">
<emphasis id="B926D14F0949B217EF2EF9CD23D24C03" box="[812,985,1553,1579]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="480">A. commersoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (western Indian Ocean speciesgroup), which is characterized by the absence of scales on the opercle and preopercle). It is clearly distinguished from its closely related species from Africa, 
<taxonomicName id="4C5276DE0949B217EE92F98523324C5A" baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1852" box="[656,825,1625,1651]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Awaous" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="480" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aeneofuscus">
<emphasis id="B926D14F0949B217EE92F98523324C5A" box="[656,825,1625,1651]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="480">A. aeneofuscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, by the following characters: breast and pectoral base naked, pectoral base with 1–3 scales in adults (vs. pectoral base usually fully scaled), and the first dorsal fin with small brown spots and no distinct black spot in young or adults (vs. with marbling of small black spots and blotches, especially pronounced posteriorly, but no distinct white-edged black spot).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
